1. How to check your current work location?
* pwd

2. How to display name of current logged-in usr?
* whoami

3. How to check system date or tme?
* date
* date +%D: displays only date
* date +%T: displays only time
* date +%H:%M: displays in the format you gave i.e, hours:minutes

4. How to display files and directory present in current location?
* ls
* ls -altrh

5. How to clear the Linux terminal?
* clear
* ctrl + l

6. Display content of a file on terminal?
* cat <file_name>

7. How to read a file and search for a word?
* less <file_name>: this will open an interactive terminal
* To search for words from top to bottom: /<word_name>
* To search next word: n
* To move to bottom line or ending of file: shift + g
* To move to top of file: p
* To search for a word from bottom to top: ?<word_name>
* To exit from file: q

8. How to view content of a file page by page?
* more <file_name>: this will also print content in terminal and remaining same as "less" command.

9. How to create a file in Linux?
* touch <file_name>

10. How to delete a file in Linux?
* rm <file_name>
* rm -rf: deadly command

11. How to edit a file in Linux?
* vi, vim, nano

12. How to create a directory/folder in Linux?
* mkdir <dir_name>

13. How to delete a directory/folder in Linux?
* rmdir <dir_name>
* rm -rf <dir_name>

14. How to change path or move to another folder in Linux?
* cd /path/to/dest
* cd ..: to go back by 1 directory
* cd /: this will move to root i.e, its like desktop in windows.

15. How to copy and paste a file from one folder to another in Linux?
* cp <source_file> <dest_path>

16. How to copy content of a file to another file in Linux?
* cp fileA fileB

17. How to cut-paste a file from one folder to another in Linux?
* mv <file_name> /dest/path

18. How to rename a file in Linux?
* mv fileA fileNewName

19. How to read or display top/bottom 5 lines from a file in Linux?
* head -5 <file_name>: for top
* tail -5 <file_name>: for bottom

20. How to sort the content from a file in Linux?
* sort <file_name>
* It is useful when you're working with data or want to sort in particular order like A to Z or something else.

Ex: type alphabets in irregular order in a file and cat it, the output will be in irregular order only.
if you use sort <file_name> then the output will be in alphabetical order.

* sort -r <file_name>: this sorts in reverse order i.e from Z to A

21. How to display UNIQUE content from a file in Linux?
* sort <file_name> | uniq
* this will remove all duplicates and only prints unique values or content.

22. A file has 9 lines
How to split this file into 3 different files in Linux?
* split -l 3 <file_name>
* -l: states till how many lines you want to split

23. How to search a word and display matching content from a file in Linux?
* grep "word" <file_name>

24. How to search multiple words and display matching content from a file in Linux?
* egrep "word1|word2" <file_name>

25. How to use WILDCARDS(*, [], {}) in Linux?
* ls file*
* touch file{1..5}: to provide rage

26. How to SHUFFLE content of file in Linux?
* shuf <file_name>

27. How to COUNT no of lines in a file in Linux?
* wc -l <file_name>

28. How to check/compare if two files are identical or not in Linux?
* cmp fileA fileB

29. How to compare and display difference between two files in Linux?
* diff -u fileA fileB
* This displays whats different between them

30. How to find a file in Linux?
* find /path/ -name <file_name>

31. How to find a file in Linux?
* updatedb
* locate <file_name>

Difference between find and locate command:
find: It goes to every path and finds the file we are searching for.
locate: it has a cache database which holds all the information, it simply goes  there and give us what we want.
-> but issues is you have to run updated to use locate command


Utility Commands:

1. How to display previously used commands in past?
* history

2. How to check syntax and options available for a command?
* help
* Ex: ls --help

3. How to read or get more info about a command?
* man
* man ls

4. How to check which executable is using a command?
* which
* Ex: which ls

5. How to use calculator in Linux?
* bc(binary calculator): It will drop you into a terminal where you can directly give what you want to run like: 9*9, 9+9
* ctrl + c to exit

6. How to check CALENDAR of last year in Linux?
* cal
* cal 2020: This will display 2020 calendar
* cal JAN 2020

7. How to check how long server has been running in Linux?
* uptime 

8. How to record your activity on terminal in a file?
* ******* script: your activity will be recorded in a file
* ctrl + d: to stop recording your activity

9. How to create a short-cut of a long command in Linux?
* alias l="ls -ltr"
* To check existing alias: alias -p
* this alias is not permanent, once you logout every short-cut will be gone.


Compress & De-compression of files/folders in Linux:

1. How to compress a single file in Linux?
* gzip -k <file_name>
* -k: keep the original and make another compressed file 

2. How to decompress a single file in Linux?
* gunzip <file_name>

3. How to compress a single folder in Linux?
* tar -czf compressedfolder.tar.gz myfolder/
* -c: compress
* -z: in gz format
* -f: to give name to compressed file
NOTE: if you compress a folder type, it becomes a file type

4. How to decompress a single folder in Linux?
* tar -xzf compressedfolder.tar.gz
* -x: extract

5. How to compress multiple files in one zipped file in Linux?
* zip myfiles.zip file1 file2

6. How to unzip a file in Linux?
* unzip myfiles.zip

7. How to list files in zipped file?
* unzip -l myfiles.zip

Q. Difference between zip, gzip, tar

8. How to download a file from internet?
* wget URL_of_file
* wget -O opt_file.txt URL_of_file: to save with custom name

9. How to call an API on Linux?
* curl http://jhjshkjsjkhs.com/random

Q. Difference between curl, wget

10. How to install an application on Linux?
* apt or yum/dnf

QQQ. 11. How to check if an application is installed or not on Linux?
* rpm -qa | grep app: for redhat
* dnf list installed
* Check for Ubuntu 

12. How to list available packages to install on Linux?
(To check if application is available to install, or what versions avilable)
* apt search <package_name>
* yum/dnf list available

13. How to start/stop a service on Linux?
* systemctl start/stop service_name
* Ex: systemctl status firewalld.service

14. How to list all services on Linux?
* systemctl list-units --type=service --all

15. How to list all existing environment variables on Linux?
* printenv
* It is OS level defining of an executable path so that OS would know where the executable is present.

16. How to ADD a new environment variable on Linux(temporary)?
* export JAVA_HOME="/usr/lib/jvm/java_v"
* export PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:#PATH
****** meaning of each command

***17. How to ADD a new environment variables permanently on linux?
* Add env variable in .bashrc file
* source .bashrc
* Ex: vim .bashrc -- define any variable in it -- save -- run source .bashrc
NOTE: this is user specific, other users cant find or use it

***18. How to print a specific column from a CSV file?
* awk -F , '{print $2}' file.csv
* -F: field separator
* Here , states that in this file all words are separated by , itself.
* $2 specifice the column we want to print.
Ex: awk -F , '{print $1,$2}' file.csv

19. How to display starting two characters of all line?
* cut -c1-2 file.txt
* cut -c3-4 file.txt

20. How to display a specific line from a file?
* sed -n '5p' file.txt: this displays 5th line

21. How to replace a specific word within a file?
* sed 's/from/to/g' file.txt
* here g is global

22. How to convert the content to Uppercase or Lowercase within a file?
* tr [:lower:] [:upper:] <file_name> : change from lowercase to upper case  
* tr [:punct:] Z file_name
* tr [:digit:] Z file_name
* tr: translate
* To delete something from file: tr -d something < file_name
* To change something: tr "what to change" "To what" < file_name

23. How to extent or shrink size of a file?
* truncate -s 100M file.txt
* -s: size
* What happens here? Linux adds some random things in that file.
* Only used for testing purpose

24. How to change user or login as different user in Linux?
* su <user_name>

25. How to exit as current user or cose terminal in Linux?
* exit


File permission:

1. chmod a+rwx file_name
* a: all
* o: other
* u: user
* g: group
* remaining you already know

2. How to change ownership of a file?
* chown root file_name

3. How to change group ownership of a file?
* chgrp root file_name

Memory Info:

1. How to check free RAM space?
* free -th
* -t: Total

Q. Difference between RAM memory and swap memory

2. How to check % memory and cpu utilized?
* top
* htop

3. How to check disk Utilization?
* du
* du myfolder: this displays how much disk myfolder used

4. How to check filesystem available and disk space allocated?
* df -h

System Info:

1. How to check hostname/machine name of your Linux server?
* hostname

2. How to check cpu/core/thread info of your Linux server?
* lscpu

3. How to check the type of architecture of your Linux server?
* arch

4. How to see the list of storage devices, disk partitions on your Linux server?
* lsbik
* lists all block devices

5. How to see OS name of Linux server?
* uname -a
* cat /etc/os-release

Process Management:

1. How to check is a process(jave) is running or not?
* ps -ef | grep java

2. How to get PID of a process?
* pgrep service_name

3. How to stop a process by PID?
* kill -9 PID
* -9: means forcefully

Why using systemctl and kill commands why why why?
systemctl will only work with services but not all processes
Ex: You are running multiple scripts then use kill

4. How to stop a process by its name?
* pkill https

5. How to see all the active jobs?
* jobs

What is job?
Any task assigned to terminal is a job to terminal 

6. How to resume a job in background?
* bg: simply run this and it will start the backgroung jobs

7. How to resume a job in foreground?
* fg

try to run sleep 10s -- ctrl z -- bg/fg

8. How to run a script in background?
* nohup ./script >/dev/null &

Networking Info:

1. How to check IP of your machine?
* ifconfig
* curl ifconfig.me

2. How to check if a server or website is accessible or not?
* ping www.google.com/IP

3. How to check if a IP:PORT is accessible and open or not?
* telnet IP PORT

4. How to check if port is open or not on our server?
* netstat -putan | grep 80

5. How to check all hubs in network path to reach a website?
* traceroute www.google.com

6. How to restart our Linux server?
* reboot

7. How to shutdown our Linux server?
* shutdown

8. How to check UserID or GroupID of a user?
* id user_name







